eorge W. Wickersham\nj has given out an interview in which he says Harding is\n.not opposed to-the league covenant entirely and will help in re\nvising it. The senator has not repudiated the statement but in\nsists he cannot tell just what he will do in the matter if elected.\nWhen the separate peace resolution was before the senate\nHarding voted for it. He even voted to carry it over the presi\ndent's veto. In his acceptance speech he officially and formally\ndeclared for separate peace when he said he would make\npeace just as quickly as a republican congress could pass a reso\nlution. Scarcely a week ago the senator declared specifically\nifpr scrapping the treaty bodily and for placing faith in the\nJtlague tribunal.\nI In other words the senator is now giving a sample of Mr.\ntacing-Both-VVays. For campaign purposes he is trying to ap\npease the league supporters. But if he was. sincere in accepting\nthe Johnso.n-Borah position and in advising that the treaty be\nscrapped then he is not sincere m the position ascribed by Wick\nersham. He cannot be both black and white. He cannot be\na' treaty assassin and a friend of the treaty at the same time,\nfortunately no one need judge the candidate by his words. His\nrecord is the thing to go by and his record is consistently anti-\nleague. If he had wanted to merely revise the covenant he\nwould have asserted himself on the side of Taft and Wilson\n.while the fight was on in the senate; He did the opposite thing\nand by his deeds let him be judged.\ni.,; For any man or any newspaper to picture Harding as a\nfriend of the treaty or the league is, in view of his record and his\njormer speeches, an amazing bit of effrontery, buch a course\nassails the intelligence of the average reader and leads to the\nImpression that the front porch gentleman is not above double\ndealing.\nI1 1 THE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nNNOUN CEMENTS that woolen mills will reopen about\nthe middle of September and that conditions are grow\ninir mw favorable in the cotton trade have combined\nduring the past week with good news concerning the business\nsituation to atfora an encouraging view ui me autumn uuwwr..\nThe Federal Reserve Board's review of conditions, as of Septem\nber!, shows steady progress toward the restoration of a normal\nbasis'of business and while such progress is possibly less marked\nir, fir.nn! and bankine than elsewhere,- it is clear that these\nbranches of activity mast eventually feel the influence of better\nConditions in other directions. A striking indication of the im\nprovement in some branches of the investment market is afford\ned by 'the Federal Reserve Board of New York, which found by\nan investigation among representative member banks that Lib-\nerty Bonds and Victory Notes bought by the customers of these\ntanks over a recent three months' period exceeded, those sold\nby about one-half.- The bank al3o reports that a large portion\ncl the recurring issues of treasury certificates is now taken by\nprivate investors who hold the certificates in most cases up to\nmaturity. The continued reports of good agricultural conditions\nhave also united with the better industrial prospects to strength\nen the conviction that there' will be a maintenance of buying\nDower and improvement in the distribution of wealth during the\ncoming months. From the Clews' Financial Review.\nIt is \"mudslinging\" for Governor Cox to expose the immense\nfund being raised in Harding's behalf but at least, as the gover\nnor has said, he cannot be accused of hounding a sick man.\nThrough the right sort of work by the accommodations bu\nreaurand full cooperation by the public most of the profiteering\n.'during the Round-Up can be eliminated Let's try it.\nThe senate committee is for the defense, not the prosecution.\nCHICAGO, Sept. 7 (A-. P.) The\nAmerican Chemical Society yesterday\npassed resolutions expressing reprret\nthat- eongsess bad not passed leglsla\ntion adequately protecting; American\ndye manufacturers and urging that\nsuch legislation be passed. Speakers\ndeclared that such legislation was\nneeded not. only to prevent Germany\nfrom dumping her output rjf dyes into\nAmerican markets but to weaken her\nmilitary strength.\nIt was pointed out that the same\nchemicals used in dyes also are used\nn explosives and poisonous bases and\nthat encoupagement of Germany's dya\nindustry gave her a latent military\nstrength.\nj ROSS IIAXGS VP UKCOKO\nEXETBR, England. Sept-\nt Norman Rosa today (Ham u\n;.rds In open water in three minutes,\nfS 4-S seconds. It was announced\nthat1 this time constituted a world's\nrecord.\n.f'lBSOX SIGXEO rort 1921\nPITTSBrilGH, Sept. 8. (A. P.)\nBarnej Dreyfus, of the Pittsburgh\nNational League baseball club, an\nnounced last night mm hs, signed\nGeorge Gibson, present manager, to\nmanaire ttie team next peason.\nST\nJLniaani iV .jaat 1\na MB\nk J AMERICA'S HOME SHOE POLISH j\nr.. .jr. i L\n9h0 A W .V\nto T7- A Ac in c. m\nShinolA\nSoften\nand,\nPrervics\nthai\nLeather\nCAMP PICIC ROBINSON, Ky, Sept.\nW X Hera on.tha banks of the\nmeandering Kentucky river, 4A can\ndidates for positions on the I92u Cen\ntra College football squad today open\ned a 10-day training seaaon In prepa\nration for the drive they hope will ro\nstilt in the winning of American col\nlegiate football honors.\nAt the outset it was made plain the\nColonels are \"layln' for Harvard.\" FMr\non October 23 the little collego that\nlast year came \"out of the sticks\" and\nwon national gridiron recognition -by\nrolling up a score of 432 points against\n1-A for their opponents, will make a\npilgrimage to Cambridge, the first\nmeeting of football talent from this\nsection and the East. Centre men\nhave their heads set to beat tho big\neastern university, and if \"praying and\nplnylng\" \"Will turn the trick, they're\ngoing to pray and play hard they\navow.\n\"Chief Myers, athletic director of\nthe Colonels, \"Bo\" McMillln, phenom\nInat caption and all-Americnn quar\nterback, and Charley McDowell, assist\nant field marshal, were first bn the\nground when the camp opened. In\naddition there ail but three members\nof last year's team and two doxen re\ncruits. Head Coach \"Uncle Charlie\"\nMoran will not arrive until September\n15, date of the closing of his engage\nment as National league umpire.\nOKI stars Ki'turn\nL Among Inst year's stars, the follow\ning put in appearance: \"Red\" Rob\nerts, \"Red\" Weaver, \"Lefty\" Whitney,\nTerry Snoddy, \"Irish\" Murphy. Bill\nJames, Sully Montgomery, \"Pap\"\nFord, Ben Creagor, Norris Armstrong,\n11111 Rlevins ar.i Hamp Tanner. Others\nare expected to arrive daily until the\ncamp's enrollment has reached prob\nably 65 or 70.\nThree hundred a.nd ten students\nhave already applied for accommoda\ntions at Centre for this fall. Last year\nthe school which turned out the \"pray-\nin' team\" boasted no more than 202\nmen in its student body it is non-\ncoeducational.\nDanville, site of the college, will ac\ncompany the team enmasse. -'Arrangements\nhave already been made for a\nspecial train to leave Danville October\n21, allowing a day in. Boston for prac\ntice on the National league baseball\ngrounds there. The retttrn trip will be\nmade by way of Niagra Falls. It Is\nLestimated 500 persons from Danville.\nLexington and Louisville will make the\ntrip Tvith the team.\nNine Games Scheduled\nThe Colonela' season schedule has\nbeen announced as follows:\nOctober 2 Morris-Harvey College\n1 (W. Va.) at Danville.\nOctober 9 Howard College (Ala.)\nat Danville.\nOctober 18 Transylvania College\nat Danville; f\nOctober 23 Harvard at Cambridge.\nOctober 30 Georgia Tech at Atlan\nta\nNovember 6 DePauw at Indianapolis.\nNovember 13 Kentuckey State at\nlexington.\nNovember 20 Virginia Polytechnic\nat LouisviUe..\nNovember 25 (Thanlcsgiving)\nGeorgetown (Ky.) at Danville.\nSEEK DYE LEGISLATION\nTO CURB FOE INDUSTRY\nwilij si:kk opinions\nTOKIO, Sept, 7. (A. P.) Con\ngressman L. C. Dyer, of St. Louis, an\nnounced here yesterday that he will\ncontinue in Japan the efforts he start.\ned in China to learn opinion of Amer-\ncans In the Far Kast concerning the\nbill hi congressional committee pro\nposing to authorize the United States\ngovernment to grant charters to Am\nericans doing -business in China. It\nis known as the federal incorporation\nin China bill.\nATLANTIC PITCIlrat GOES UP\nATLANTA, rta., Sept. 8. (A. P.)\nPitcher Tom Sheehan, of the Atlanta\nSouthern Association baseball club,\nhas been sold to the New York Amer-\ncans.\nCI L\n4 JgSST m- IA\n.-Y. a,---''\"! h\nmm\nOREGON'S TWO COLLEGE\nSCHEDULES ARE HEAVY\nPORTLAND, Ore., 8ept 8. (A. P.)\nOregon's two members of the Paci\nfic Coast Conference, the University\nof Oregon and the Oregon Agricultural\nCollege, have heavy- schedules ahead\nfor the 1920 season.\nUniversity of Oregon's schedule ha\nbeen described as \"perfect\" by the\nOregon coaches, as U caHs for games\nagainst light teams early in the season.\nwith the Important conference game\nnear the close. The Aggies' schedule.\naccording to \"Jimmy\" Richardson,\nathletie manager at the college, is the\nheaviest of any conference team.\nOregon llias line Schedule\nOregon opens with a practice game\nagainst the Multnomah Amateur Ath\nletic Club of Portland or the Willam\nette University of Salem. The first In\ntercollegiate game will tie against the\nUniversity of Idaho at Eugene, 0't.\n23. These two games. It is thought,\nwill put the team into good shape for\nthe conference game against Stanford\nUnivemity at Palo Alio, Cal., Oct. 30.\nA game at Ogden against the Univer\nsity of Utah may be played next. The\nUniversity of Washington plays Ore\ngon at Biifcene Nov. 13 and the annual\ngame between Oregon and the Oregon\nAKgies will hettiPbl at Corvallis, Nov\n20, Qn&UM'u Uut f axue wiil b against,\nAn\nThis section cerfairiltj owes\na lot to th e a u to m o\nSelect your tim ac\ncrding ta th road\nthey hava to traval\nIn sandy or hilly coun\ntry, wherever the going\nis ap